Measuring Meta=E2=80=99s Spending
-------------------------

Still, metrics matter, particularly given the amount of money that Meta pla=
ns on spending, and the problem with promises of broad applicability and wi=
de-ranging upside in the short, medium, and long-terms is that it is hard t=
o hold management accountable for their spending. This is exacerbated by th=
e fact that so much of Meta=E2=80=99s investment is in R&D, which goes unde=
r the line, and capex, which goes into Cost of Revenue but which is only re=
alized as depreciation over five years (and, as an aside, kudos to Meta for=
 sticking with a five-year depreciation schedule, instead of the six years =
that many of its peers have switched to even as they are ramping up spendin=
g on GPUs, which likely burn out faster than CPUs).

